c, Jeanmarie, Marcel.","French and Walloon: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Eberhard</i> (see   Eberhardt  ).","English: variant of   Everett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Evard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Henri, Jean-Claude, Remy.","French and Swiss French: shortened form of   Evrard  ."]},{"name":"Eberhardt","meanings":["German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>eber</i> ‘wild boar’ (Old High German, Old Saxon <i>ebur</i>) + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]}]},{"name":"dit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Chun, Hin, Kwan, Fung, Wai, Yau, Chi, Chi Shing, Chow, Hon, Hong, Kit Man.  Korean Chung, Pak.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 薛, see   Xue  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Xue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Jian, Hua, Liang, Wei, Yuan, Biao, Chun, Fei, Lixin, Ming, Qi, Min, Tian, Yiming.  Vietnamese Lan, Hao, Huan.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 薛, originally denoting a ‘type of grass’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Xue (薛), the name of an ancient state (originally located in Shandong province) dating back to the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname. (ii) from the placename Xue (薛), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to Meng Chang Jun (Lord Meng Chang), a famous prince of the state of Qi, known as one of “the four princes during the Warring States period (475–221  BC )”. (iii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Gan (叱干) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) borne by descendants of Xue Huai Yi (薛懷義), a famous general of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD )."]}]},{"name":"An